    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2656861919" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2656861919" />
    <a title="Roman Clodia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/56111743-roman-clodia"><img alt="Roman Clodia" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1464021031p2/56111743.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2656861919?book_show_action=true">Jan 04, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Roman Clodia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Roman Clodia" href="/user/show/56111743-roman-clodia">Roman Clodia</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2656861919" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14398383987053502853">An ambitious novel of ideas, this deals both thematically and in narrative terms with issues of a woman&apos;s personal willed disintegration and a final move towards her unification of disparate selves. <br/><br/>Structurally, the book is complicated: divided into five sections, the first four each comprise a chronological extract from a novel called &apos;Free Women&apos; followed by segments from four &apos;notebooks&apos;, each designated by a colour. &apos;Black&apos; deals with Anna&apos;s experiences in Africa towards the end of WW2, the</span>
  <span id="freeText14398383987053502853" style="display:none">An ambitious novel of ideas, this deals both thematically and in narrative terms with issues of a woman's personal willed disintegration and a final move towards her unification of disparate selves. <br /><br />Structurally, the book is complicated: divided into five sections, the first four each comprise a chronological extract from a novel called 'Free Women' followed by segments from four 'notebooks', each designated by a colour. 'Black' deals with Anna's experiences in Africa towards the end of WW2, the source of a successful novel she went on to write; 'Red' is an account of her political life, especially her disillusionment with the Communist Party; 'Yellow' is perhaps one of the most interesting, comprising as it does the notes for, and extracts from, a novel that Anna is writing called 'The Shadow of the Third': we can find pieces of Anna in the character of Ella, and also get Anna's commentary on the fiction, a dizzying display of narrative complications; and 'Blue' is a diary belonging to Anna. The final fifth section, the 'Golden' notebook, is an attempt to reintegrate Anna from across all these sources.<br /><br />Written in 1962 though set between WW2 and the late 1950s (in the background we get glimpses of Hiroshima, Korea, Macarthyism, Hungary and Czechoslovakia, the death of Stalin, apartheid and the imprisonment of a Nelson Mandela-style figure), this must have been provocatively shocking with its open discussion of sexuality: Anna and Ella, her fictional alter ego, conduct a series of affairs with married men, analysed with merciless detail. <br /><br />This is not a book about prose style: it's not full of smart phrases or poetic diction - though it can be funny with hits of satire (Anna's encounters with film and TV makers wanting to film her novel; or the blisteringly acidic exposé of Marion who wants to write and send food parcels to the Mandela-alike in prison, using adopted soundbites from the press - Anna's sardonic response: "it's not a nice organised prison like Brixton... what did you think? - that they had visiting hours and rights and things like that?")<br /><br />There are a few places where the length can feel a little tiring, the direction can become a touch wavering. But I enjoyed the ways it probes the psyche of Anna/Ella and the attention it pays to acts of narrativisation. Narrative, it turns out is both a survival mechanism for Anna and also a way to contain her separate selves: only at the end, via the Golden Notebook, does she come back together again.<br /><br />So an elaborate structure combines with a bold vision here: in places it reminded me of de Beauvoir's <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/19528.The_Mandarins" title="The Mandarins by Simone de Beauvoir" rel="nofollow noopener">The Mandarins</a> but overall I'd say this is more intellectually than emotionally engaging - clever, for sure, fiercely intelligent... but a touch cold? <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="14398383987053502853" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

