<span id="freeTextContainer1710300705988105586"><blockquote>
  <i>That’s the dark secret of our time, no one mentions it, but every time one opens a door one is greeted by a shrill, desperate and inaudible scream.</i>
</blockquote><br/>This book raped me. It raped my mind with its insightfulness, raped my heart with its relatability, and raped the 20th century in half with its surgical dissection of the 1950’s zeitgeist. <br/><br/>I would love to write a more detailed review, but this novel is an ocean, and diving into any one given point would inevitably leave out unfathomed depths. I re</span>
  <span id="freeText1710300705988105586" style="display:none"><blockquote>
  <i>That’s the dark secret of our time, no one mentions it, but every time one opens a door one is greeted by a shrill, desperate and inaudible scream.</i>
</blockquote><br />This book raped me. It raped my mind with its insightfulness, raped my heart with its relatability, and raped the 20th century in half with its surgical dissection of the 1950’s zeitgeist. <br /><br />I would love to write a more detailed review, but this novel is an ocean, and diving into any one given point would inevitably leave out unfathomed depths. I read it in tandem with a good friend and after finishing we sat on a balcony one evening and talked about it at length while drinking wine and looking out over a mosaic-like cityscape dotted with the myriad lives of strangers seen or suspected through tiny backlit windows. And that is how I would like to remember this book.</span>
