  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2621156985" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2621156985" />
    <a title="Clif Hostetler" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/793473-clif-hostetler"><img alt="Clif Hostetler" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1593302055p2/793473.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2621156985?book_show_action=true">Jan 07, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Clif Hostetler" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Clif Hostetler" href="/user/show/793473-clif-hostetler">Clif Hostetler</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Audiobook " href="/book/show/22291730-the-golden-notebook">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/793473-clif-hostetler?shelf=novel">novel</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2621156985" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8364743105605691532">Anna Wulf (main character in this novel) is a writer, communist, ex-communist, single mother, and sexually involved with a prolific series of men. She has had one successful book in her past, but since then all her writing has been confined to four notebooks, each a different color reflecting a different part of her life in the 1940s and 50s. The black one contains recollections of her youthful wartime years in Rhodesia, experiences that went into her first novel. In the red notebook she reflect</span>
  <span id="freeText8364743105605691532" style="display:none">Anna Wulf (main character in this novel) is a writer, communist, ex-communist, single mother, and sexually involved with a prolific series of men. She has had one successful book in her past, but since then all her writing has been confined to four notebooks, each a different color reflecting a different part of her life in the 1940s and 50s. The black one contains recollections of her youthful wartime years in Rhodesia, experiences that went into her first novel. In the red notebook she reflects on her later life in London’s Communist and intellectual circles. The blue notebook analyzes her fraught relations with men most of whom are married (not to her). The yellow notebook contains her fragmentary attempts at a new novel which in many ways parallels her own life. <br /><br />Toward the end of the book Anna is struggling emotionally (i.e. "going mad") and the fragmentation in her life represented by maintaining four separate notebooks seems to be a factor in her mental torment. So Anna decides to tie all the threads of her life back together into the fifth notebook, gold in color. It's not clear that the golden notebook played a significant therapeutic role in her recovery, but the book does end on a positive note with many of the book's former leftist characters having evolved into conventional participants in bourgeoisie life.<br /><br />When the book was first published in 1962 the portion of the book that addresses the internal issues within the British Communist Party would have been of compelling interest. Today it seems to be distant news of little pertinence. The book's narrative is critical of Stalinism and the internal purges that were taking place within the party. (I can remember the 1950s when fear of the Communist Party was similar to today's fear of Islamic terrorists.) <br /><br />This book has the reputation of having feminism as one of its themes. The portions of the book's narrative that describes the current life of Anna and friends is entitled "Free Women." It's not clear to me if Anna is intended to be a model "free woman" or is a victim of male dominated society causing her to "go mad." In either case there's frequent explicit sex described in this book including in one case a detailed description of inconveniences related to mensuration. However, there's no hint provided as to how Anna manages to avoid unwanted pregnancy.<br /><br />I rate books on how I react emotionally to it. Consequently, even books that are well written by talented writers such as Doris Lessing can make me feel miserable. This book is a long drawn-out description of "going mad." Going mad is not a pleasant thing to experience, and reading about it isn't either. Thus I gave it one star because listening to the audio of this book was for me a miserable grind.<br /><br />The following is a link to quotes from "The Golden Notebook":<br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/work/quotes/99441-the-golden-notebook">https://www.goodreads.com/work/quotes...</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="8364743105605691532" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

